\meta{status}{to-buy}
\meta{price}{$2,399+}

\p{Bambu Lab H2C multi-material FDM 3D printer. Vortek hotend-change system with 6 interchangeable contactless hotends, enabling up to 7 materials per print without purge waste. 325 × 320 × 325 mm build volume. Active heated chamber (65°C), heated bed (120°C), nozzle temps to 350°C. 59 sensors, quad-camera computer vision. Expands to 24 filaments via AMS.}

\subtree{\title{Justification for immediate purchase}
\taxon{remark}
\p{Mr. Ziegel's BCI fabrication pipeline requires this printer \strong{now} for three converging reasons:}
\ol{
\li{\strong{Flexible material printing for BCI wearables.} The right hotend prints TPU 95A HF / 90A / 85A -- the exact shore hardnesses needed for electrode gaskets, skin-contact headband liners, and conformable fNIRS optode holders. ShitBCI (our in-house OpenBCI fork) needs rapid iteration on comfort geometry before committing to injection molds. TPU gaskets printed on a lesser machine lack the dimensional accuracy to maintain consistent electrode-scalp impedance.}
\li{\strong{Full build volume for headset-scale parts.} 325 × 320 × 325 mm prints an entire adult Ultracortex-class headframe in one piece -- no seam lines, no bonded joints that crack under repeated don/doff cycles. The Uncut Gem magnetometer enclosure (\ref{bcf-0031}) and fNIRS sensor housings (\ref{bcf-0011}, \ref{bcf-0033}) also fit within this volume as single-print assemblies.}
\li{\strong{Multi-material for functional prototypes.} Rigid PLA/PETG structural frame + flexible TPU gaskets + soluble PVA supports in a single print eliminates manual assembly of the 3--5 part sub-assemblies currently needed for each headset iteration. This collapses a 2-day print-sand-bond-test cycle into a 6-hour single-print-test cycle.}
}
}

\subtree{\title{Key specifications}
\taxon{remark}
\ul{
\li{Build volume: 325 × 320 × 325 mm}
\li{Hotend system: Vortek -- 6 contactless hotend slots, zero-purge material changes}
\li{Max nozzle temp: 350°C (supports PA/Nylon, PC, carbon fiber composites)}
\li{Max bed temp: 120°C}
\li{Active heated chamber: 65°C (prevents warping in ABS/ASA/PA enclosure prints)}
\li{TPU support: 95A HF, 90A, 85A on right hotend (manual feed via AMS HT bypass)}
\li{Sensors: 59 (filament runout, vibration compensation, chamber monitoring)}
\li{Vision: quad-camera system for first-layer inspection and spaghetti detection}
\li{Multi-material: up to 7 simultaneous materials, 24 via AMS expansion}
}
}

