\subtree{\title{Fabrication roadmap}
\taxon{protocol}
\ol{
\li{\strong{Week 1:} Print ShitBCI headframe v0.1 in PETG. Validate 10-20 electrode positions against modified Ultracortex geometry. Full build volume allows single-piece print.}
\li{\strong{Week 2:} Print TPU 90A electrode gaskets and comfort liners. Fit-test with Cyton board + dry comb electrodes (\ref{bcf-0006}). Measure impedance delta vs. bare electrode contact.}
\li{\strong{Week 3:} Multi-material print -- PETG frame + TPU gaskets + PVA supports in single job. Validate snap-fit tolerances for electrode units.}
\li{\strong{Week 4:} Print Uncut Gem magnetometer enclosure (\ref{bcf-0031}) in ABS with integrated laser/photodiode alignment features. Print fNIRS sensor housings for PLUX optodes.}
\li{\strong{Ongoing:} Iterate headset geometry based on EEG signal quality data. Each iteration is a 4--6 hour print-to-test cycle. Accumulate design knowledge for eventual injection mold tooling.}
}
}

\subtree{\title{Why not a cheaper printer}
\taxon{remark}
\p{The existing on-site FDM printer (\ref{bcf-0006}) lacks:}
\ul{
\li{Heated chamber -- ABS/ASA/PA prints warp, making enclosures unreliable}
\li{Multi-material capability -- rigid + flexible in one print is impossible}
\li{TPU reliability -- Bowden-tube extruders jam on shore 85A--90A filaments}
\li{Build volume -- full headframes require splitting and bonding, introducing mechanical weak points at exactly the locations where electrode pressure matters most}
}
\p{The H2C's direct-drive right hotend with AMS HT bypass is specifically engineered for reliable flexible filament feeding. This is not a nice-to-have -- it is the critical path for ShitBCI prototyping before Mr. Ziegel commits to injection mold tooling ($5,000--$15,000 per mold).}
}
